## 9. Session State Machine

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> idle
    idle --> awaiting_document : User selects Split/Protect/Unlock/Convert sub-type
    idle --> awaiting_compression_level : User selects Compress
    idle --> collecting_merge_files : User selects Merge
    idle --> awaiting_convert_type : User selects Convert

    awaiting_compression_level --> awaiting_document : User picks Low/Medium/High

    awaiting_convert_type --> awaiting_document : User picks a conversion type

    awaiting_document --> awaiting_split_range : PDF received (Split flow)
    awaiting_document --> awaiting_password_protect : PDF received (Protect flow)
    awaiting_document --> awaiting_password_unlock : PDF received (Unlock flow)
    awaiting_document --> [*] : PDF received (Compress/Convert → process & clear)

    awaiting_split_range --> [*] : Range text received → process & clear
    awaiting_password_protect --> [*] : Password received → process & clear
    awaiting_password_unlock --> [*] : Password received → process & clear

    collecting_merge_files --> collecting_merge_files : Another PDF received
    collecting_merge_files --> [*] : "Done Merging" tapped → process & clear

    idle --> idle : User types "clear", "reset", "menu", "hi", "hello"
```

---

## 10. Concurrency & Rate Limiting

### Global Semaphore (pdfWorker)

PDF processing operations (Ghostscript, LibreOffice, `pdf-lib`) are CPU and memory intensive. To prevent the server from being overwhelmed, `pdfWorker.js` implements a **Semaphore** that limits concurrent heavy jobs to **3 at a time**.

```js
class Semaphore {
    constructor(maxCount) { ... }
    async acquire() { ... }  // blocks if maxCount reached
    release() { ... }        // unblocks the next waiting task
}

const globalLimit = new Semaphore(3);
```

All public methods of `PDFWorker` are automatically wrapped with `runWithLimit()` at module initialization time using prototype introspection:

```js
for (const key of Object.getOwnPropertyNames(PDFWorker.prototype)) {
    if (key !== 'constructor' && typeof workerInstance[key] === 'function') {
        workerInstance[key] = (...args) => runWithLimit(() => originalMethod(...args));
    }
}
```

Excess requests queue up and are processed in FIFO order once a slot opens.

### Daily User Limit

Each user is limited to **5 operations per day** (tracked by `SessionService.dailyLimitCache`). The check occurs in `handleInteractiveSelection()` before any session state is set. The counter is reset automatically when the 24-hour TTL expires.

---

## 11. Safety & Validation Rules

| Rule | Where Enforced | Detail |
|---|---|---|
| Max PDF pages | `pdfWorker.mergePdfs()`, `pdfWorker.splitPdf()` | 200 pages per input PDF |
| Max file size | `botController.handleDocument()` | 25 MB per uploaded file |
| Accepted MIME types | `botController.handleDocument()` | `application/pdf`, `image/jpeg`, `image/png`, `.docx`, `.doc` |
| Child process timeout | `pdfWorker.js` — all Ghostscript/LibreOffice calls | 30 seconds |
| Session TTL | `services/session.js` | Session auto-expires after 15 minutes of inactivity |
| Daily operation limit | `botController.handleInteractiveSelection()` | 5 operations per user per 24 hours |
| Concurrent jobs | `services/pdfWorker.js` — Semaphore | Max 3 simultaneous heavy jobs |
| Temp file cleanup | `services/cleanup.js` | Files older than 15 minutes are auto-deleted |
| Race condition guard | `botController.handleDocument()` | Session re-fetched from cache after download to get latest state |

---

## 12. API Reference — WhatsApp Cloud API

The application communicates exclusively with the **Meta Graph API v18.0**.

| Endpoint | Method | Used For |
|---|---|---|
| `/{phone_number_id}/messages` | `POST` | Sending text, interactive, and document messages |
| `/{media_id}` | `GET` | Resolving a WhatsApp media ID to a temporary download URL |
| `/{phone_number_id}/media` | `POST` | Uploading a processed file to WhatsApp media servers |

All requests include the `Authorization: Bearer <WHATSAPP_TOKEN>` header.  
Media downloads additionally send `User-Agent` and `Accept-Encoding` headers to satisfy WhatsApp CDN requirements.

---

## 13. Limitations & Known Constraints

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Review these before deploying to production.

| Limitation | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No persistent storage** | Sessions and rate-limit counters live in-process memory. A server restart clears all state. |
| **Single process** | Not clustered; a single Node.js process handles all traffic. Heavy GS/LibreOffice operations block a Semaphore slot. |
| **Hardcoded tool paths** | Ghostscript and LibreOffice paths are hardcoded for Windows. Must be updated for Linux or if installed to a non-standard path. |
| **PDF → DOCX quality** | LibreOffice's PDF-to-DOCX import is experimental; complex layouts will not convert accurately. |
| **PDF → JPG: first page only** | Only `page-1.jpg` is sent to the user even if the PDF has multiple pages. |
| **No end-to-end encryption at rest** | Files are written to `/tmp` in plain form. They are deleted, but are not encrypted on disk. |
| **Password security** | Ghostscript's PDF encryption uses RC4 (compatible with `CompatibilityLevel=1.4`). This is not considered cryptographically strong by modern standards. |
| **WhatsApp file size limit** | WhatsApp enforces its own upload limit of 100 MB for documents. The bot further restricts downloads to 25 MB. |
| **No test suite** | `package.json` has a placeholder test script. No automated tests exist. |

---

## 14. Deployment Guide

### Prerequisites

- Node.js (v18+ recommended)
- npm
- Ghostscript 10.x installed
- LibreOffice 7.x installed
- A publicly accessible HTTPS URL (required by Meta webhooks) — use [ngrok](https://ngrok.com) for local development

### Local Development

```powershell
# 1. Clone the repository
cd "d:\Webdev\QuickPDF Assistant"

# 2. Install dependencies
npm install

# 3. Configure environment
copy .env.example .env
# Edit .env with your credentials

# 4. Start the server
node index.js
```

### Connecting to WhatsApp (Meta Developer Setup)

1. Go to [developers.facebook.com](https://developers.facebook.com) and create a new App of type **Business**.
2. Add the **WhatsApp** product.
3. Under *WhatsApp > Configuration*, set the Callback URL to your public HTTPS URL + `/webhook`.
4. Set the Verify Token to match `VERIFY_TOKEN` in your `.env`.
5. Subscribe to the `messages` webhook field.
6. Copy your `Phone Number ID` and a permanent Access Token into `.env`.

### Production Considerations

- Run behind a reverse proxy (NGINX / Caddy) with TLS termination.
- Use a process manager like **PM2** to keep the process alive and auto-restart on crashes.
- Consider Redis for session storage to survive restarts and support horizontal scaling.
- Mount `/tmp` on a RAM disk (tmpfs on Linux) for faster I/O on ephemeral files.
- Add structured logging (e.g., Winston or Pino) for observability.
